The interesting question is then - why did the US not attack the USSR in 1941?  Stalin had murdered about 10 - 20 million of his own people by then over the last 15 years.<br>
This tells you clearly, that &quot;humanitarian&quot; concerns make a decent justification for war, but very rarely are the reason for it.<br>
To give you another example, for 50 years we have noted the violation of human rights and extermination (cultural and physical) in Tibet after the annexation by China. Nevertheless noone asks for an invasion of the area, despite the fact that China admittedly has WMDs too <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=260848">Shamu Whitewale</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
