<br>
Be warned it has not been totally proof read, nor does it contain everything that I haven't quite remembered.<br>
<br>
<br>
First of all, no weapons have been found.<br>
<br>
Most people seem to think this is pretty inconsequential, in fact it's very much a critical problem.<br>
<br>
It means one of the following. (by 'no weapons existed' I do not mean 'ever', I mean in the lead up to the war').<br>
<br>
1.) No weapons existed. We knew that.<br>
<br>
If this was true, it shows lack of trust in the public, they wouldn't have said because they knew we would not have supported the war. This is a bad thing, it would have shown that the truth is not what the government was really concerned with, only public opinion. <br>
<br>
2.) No weapons existed. We didn't know that.<br>
<br>
First of all, it would not have shown Iraqi compliance, as they didn't explain where it all went. It's a scary thought, that the US intelligence agencies couldn't work out where thousands of tonnes of biological and chemical weapons were, and what happened to them. If we claimed they existed, then had no evidence of where the hell they went, isn't it safe to assume that the US Intelligence is flawed in that respect. <br>
<br>
Seeing that the US intelligence was key to prooving 'threat' and 'capability' would this fact erode your confidence in those previous statements?<br>
<br>
3.) Weapons existed. We knew where they were.<br>
<br>
If we had known where the weapons were, we would have found them allready, it's relativley simple. It's kinda scary that we knew where they were, and that they could fall into the hands of the terrorists and now we don't know where the hell they are!<br>
<br>
4.) Weapons existed. We didn't know where they were.<br>
<br>
Remember, that this means the weapons 'existed' when the war started. Remember George Tennets report on Iraq Early October 2002? (I think), it claimed that Saddam hussein is most likely to give lots of weapons to Terrorists, and use those weapons if he thought it was his one of his last chances for vengance. This is the man who is head of the CIA.<br>
<br>
Do you find it scary that we ploughed in knowing he had shit loads of weapons, and that he is likely to give them to terrorists, but we thought it's not a big thing that we don't know where they are? Because I think that's a massive problem. <br>
<br>
Honestly speaking, we pretty much did know where they were. We gave lots of evidence to weapons inspectors in the attempts of catching them with their pants down. The intelligence however, came to nothing. The type of clean up operation that would have gone on in the sites that were given to inspectors, would have been so unbelievabely massive, it would have taken incompotence on behalf of the intelligence services to miss it. See point 1.)<br>
<br>
To carry on though...<br>
<br>
The Security situation was amazingly overhyped.<br>
<br>
Lets look at the details.<br>
<br>
When resolution 1441 passed, shortly after America seized on potshots taken by Iraq at aeroplanes patrolling the no-fly zone as a reason why Iraq was in material breach of the resolution. <br>
<br>
A Terrorist camp to the north was claimed to be a poisons factory used by Al`qaeda. American officials also tried to link this camps to the discovery of quantities of Ricin in the UK. UK officials laughed this off and the camp hasn't had any traces as far as I am aware of Ricin. <br>
<br>
This terrorist camp was also used as a big deal as to why Iraq was harbouring terrorist, but, neglected to mention very often that it was in the far north of Iraq near Iran's border, and has been outside the sphere of operations of the Iraqi army for the last 10 or so years.<br>
<br>
Before the war, it was reported that Saddam put WMD under the control of regional commanders. First of all, how did you know that? and second of all, why were none found if this was the case. <br>
<br>
It was claimed Iraqi scientists would spill the beans days after Saddam was toppled and lead you right to the WMD, or where they were destroyed. This has not been the case.<br>
<br>
It's difficult to beleive that with a WMD program as extensive as Iraq's was beleived to be, that no-one in Iraq would come forward to show where they were. I'm fairly sure that not all of them were hefty Baath Loyalists.<br>
<br>
The Missiles discovered a month or two before the war that exceeded the limitations impossed by something like 15%. This was siezed upon as a major demonstration of Iraqi non-compliance. Now, common sense tells me, that If they were going to design missiles that they wanted to be in excess of UN requirements, they would have done it by something useful, like 300%, as it was, the missiles only had a range that put 100 more camles in range. It was also a bit up in the air whether it was tested with a guidance system, which if you know newtons laws, would have probably been less than the required range.<br>
<br>
<br>
We all know the story of Uranium Yellow-cake from Nigeria, which is generally regarded to be untrue.<br>
<br>
There's the Aluminium tubing that was claimed to be used for the processing of Uranium. However, tests made on them showed that they tended to shatter when spun at the speeds necessary to do it.<br>
<br>
There were also the masses and masses of documents that were 'found' at a scientists home. Exactly what happened to those again? I would have thought that if it was evidence you were looking for, that would be it right there.<br>
<br>
The truck containers apparently found, that in Colin powells speach to the UN security council were described as mobile chemical labratories. But in real life, when discovered there was neither that many of them, nor were they as complex as Mr Powell had described, nor was it strikingly obvious that they were used for chemical manafacturing.<br>
<br>
6, or 12, I forget how many Chemical shells were discovered in a depot somewhere, it was claimed that it's plainly obvious that this is a complete material breach, yet it was a) 0.1 % of their supposed aresnal, and were found strewn about a munitions dump,  even if Iraq were hiding as many weapons as claimed, or that they destroyed them all, I think that it's fairly safe to assume that these were forgetton about.<br>
<br>
Now, I'm not saying that there was no chance that Iraq had weapons, I'm saying that the evidence was hyped up above what it actually was.<br>
<br>
This means that the security threat, and the need to take out Saddam because of the WMD threat was not as great as claimed. Either that, or the Intelligence services were relativley incompotent or incredibly unlucky. Either way, I do not put that much confidence at all in the evidence placed in the public domain.<br>
<br>
Now, lets talk about the 'Politics behind it'<br>
<br>
I consider myself a better political analyst than the average schmoe, a lot of political speeches are aimed at people dumber than myself, which makes it slightly easier to pick up on the things that are blatantly not being said.<br>
<br>
The reasons that were mainly stated before the war, were the big three, WMD, Defying the UN, contacts with Al`qaeda. there was a little bit about him being a bastard.<br>
<br>
You can argue it any way you want to that it was all about him being a bastard, but that really wasn't stated much until the month or so before the war started, not much at all in the year before that.<br>
<br>
I'd say that you could break it down 50/25/20/5 in percentage about what was being said about those big three, seeing as it was a very political justification in that it was attempting to manipulate the public like all politics.<br>
<br>
Now, post war, the justification is 5/1/4/90. That switch is massivley important. And shows the politics of the situation. Now that the mass graves, and the horror of saddams regime is down, it's only natural politics to use that as a good side to convince people. And to be honest, I was allready convinced of that, and I think a good many people were.<br>
<br>
The politics of this is fairly straight forward, it makes it harder for the average joe to disagree with the war. It's because people generally have short term memories about politics in the media. But to explain and justify the reasons behind the war, you have to adequately explain why the speeches have shifted so massivley from one thing to another pre and post war.<br>
<br>
The thing is, if the justifications were prooven, there would not have been such a drastic change of speech content, and I think that is an absolutley critical note to point out. It shows how much the proof was highly political, attempting to shift opinions by manipulation. I'm not being conspiratorial here or anything, it's just what politics generally is.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, lets talk about Al`qaeda.<br>
<br>
In the cave systems and camps that were overrun by US forces, no traces of chemical, or biological weapons have yet been found, asside from traces of Ricin, which to be honest I don't really count, as anyone with an A-level in Chemistry can make Ricin in reasonably large quantities with easily obtainable equipment.<br>
<br>
If there was a neat flow of chemical and biological weaponry, and training to al`qaeda, I would have pressumed that something more substantial had been found.<br>
<br>
<br>
Not only that, If any terrorist cells planning biological or chemical attacks had been cracked, it would have been amazingly well publicised as it would directly proove the reasoning for the war itself.<br>
<br>
Now, the Anthrax attack on the US was found to be a deadly, yet low grade form of anthrax. Anyone with an A-level in biology has the expertise to cultivate this form of anthrax, with access to the original biological samples. Proof of involvement you say? Of course! Not. Before the anthrax attacks, It wasn't actually too hard to obtain samples of Anthrax of this quality, as the controls weren't too heavy.<br>
<br>
<br>
There was a report on BBC panorama after the anthrax scare at how journalists managed to purchase quantities of the smallpox virus with ease and little to no questions.<br>
<br>
Now, the scary thing is the Ex-USSR. Have you any idea how much Weapons grade material is missing, and how much radiological material (radioactive cadmium samples) are missing?<br>
<br>
If I recall (I could be mistaken) the USSR has been unable to adequatley dispose of massive quantities of Plutonium it had stockpiled in weapons due for Treaty-based decommisioning because they were out of money (donations?). Hey presto, a few months later, organised criminals in the Former-USSR were found to be in control of large, yet not critical masses of weapons grade Plutonium. More was discovered in Turkey later.<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, lets look at North Korea, which in my mind is far bigger threat.<br>
<br>
It's widely beleived (if i'm not mistaken) that North Korea has a massive stockpile of unconvential weapons, both chemical and biological (i'm not that sure thought to be honest). You have no idea what they are doing in terms of their relationship with terror.<br>
<br>
They are reprocessing Uranium, the detection of compounds of flourine have been discovered that are a tell-tale sign of this. They are beleived to have a non-trivial arsenal of nuclear weaponry at the moment. The only thing stopping them creating a nuclear weapon, is a trigger (Neutron source), this is normally another highly decaying radioactive compound (although North Korea has been known to be resourceful). This compound is detectable, but due to his extremely low half life, when you detect it, it's pretty logical to assume that a nuclear detonation is going to occour within a week, maybe two at the outside.<br>
<br>
They have missile technology which can hit some of the most highly populated cities in the world, and at a pinch, may well be able to hit mainland USA with a missile. The warheads they may be able to carry would probably be low yeild 20KT type of affairs, but enough to bring death and destruction of an unprecedented level to the US.<br>
<br>
The regime and country are currently in a downward spiral, and is highly unpredictable, and no-one can really tell whether they would seriously launch a massive attack of conventional, or non-conventional means, that could well possibly kill millions of people in a short a span as a few days provided all their other options were exhausted. One thing is certain, like Iraq, the safety of the Korean continent cannot be assured while the current Stalinist regime is in place.<br>
<br>
Not only this, they have been prooved of exporting weapons, and weapons technology to other countries, they are poor, and don't really care much for ideology of others, simply money. They have threatened (if they haven't allready done so) exporting nuclear technologies to other countries for money.<br>
<br>
It's probably safe to say that human rights in North Korea, and the lack of freedom far exceeds the abuses in Iraq, I'm not going to discern between ordering the execution of 10,000 people, and willingly letting people die of starvation but not caring, because in my mind they're pretty much the same.<br>
<br>
North Korea has also been misbehaving for the last 5 years, and the nature of the regime, makes it unlikely for them to dis-continue doing so.<br>
<br>
Now, with that in mind, you have an almost identical situation to Iraq, but arguably more likely to proliferate it's weapons for money, you have an un-godly and vastly imminent threat over Iraq, yet there is no need for a war?<br>
<br>
The main difference is two fold, firstly that North Korea can be bought off, but most people think you shouldn't give in to Nuclear blackmail. and Secondly, they are actually capable of causing harm to the US, it's allies, and it's interests.<br>
<br>
<br>
For the UN side of it, and the breaching of resolutions. I'm going to bring up the one that makes you roll your eyes. Yes Israel.<br>
<br>
Israel has far more breachs of UN resolutions than Iraq, and far more resultions going against it. Now, you may claim that it's because 'Those resolutions are bullshit, because Israel has done nothing wrong and the US knows that'. <br>
<br>
This is not the case, if it were, and the resolutions were stupid, ridiculous et al, then the US would have vetoed it, it has done before not just a couple of times either. The only reasons the US would have let those resolutions through, is because of A) International politics or B) Because it didn't think they were too bad.<br>
<br>
So, if the case was B, you are actually saying that you are agreeing with the resolution, but not upholding it for some unbeknownst reason.<br>
<br>
If it's International policitics, it's basically saying that voting in resolutions aren't really because of the substance but because of the people sitting round the table. That is a deep, and scary thought if you really think deeply about it's consequences.<br>
<br>
Now, it all stems, In my opinion from post 9/11 America. You see Threats, Terrorists, Horror, Fear in the world around you. I don't blame you to be honest.<br>
<br>
The main reason you want to solve all these 'problems' like Iraq that you see in the world, is because you don't want to repeat the problems of the past.<br>
<br>
A usual argument I hear is that 'This is a new world, we can no longer sit back and wait for things to happen, we must deal with them'.<br>
<br>
The problem is the pre-emptive action or preventative action that is your current doctrine is both mis-guided and in-adequate in regards to terrorism.<br>
<br>
Fine, you took out saddam for supposed massive links with terror, and supposed massive stockpiles in WMD and all it's breachs of UN resolutions that you arbitrarily care about.<br>
<br>
But you are repeating the main constituent causes in the world by ignoring the problems.<br>
<br>
You seem to be heading along the lines of ignoring key dictatorships / really bad human rights records and countries with problems because they are 'on your side'.<br>
<br>
How did Saddam get to the point he did?<br>
&quot;He was a Son-of-a-bitch, but he was OUR Son-of-a-bitch&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Now, in summary, because this has been hella long is that <br>
<br>
A) The reasons for war were over-hyped. Public Opinion was more important than truth.<br>
B) There were bigger threats in any, and all departments that Saddam was a threat with.<br>
C) In both the war on terror, and the bigger picture, you seem to be ignoring the key problems that caused this all to go on in the first place.<br>
<br>
<br>
What I cannot stand are those who are strictly anti-bush, anti-war for whatever reason. I'm no pacifist, I'll certainly stand up and call for a war, and hell, i had lots of arguments with friends about the war before, and yes I was arguing for it. I'm kind of a devils advocate most of the time anyways.<br>
<br>
My problem is that while I support the 'war' itself and the troops, next to unconditionally. I feel that the big picture of evidence, and things in the public domain doesn't make enough sense to justify all the reasons that were being touted for the war. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://216.94.170.106/phpBB2/images/avatars/19834029863f67d57cdd2ec.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
<!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;font-family:times new roman;font-size:x-small;">free speech is a God-given right....unless you disagree with the President and/or Republican Party. In that case, you're providing aid &amp; comfort to the enemy, if not comitting outright treason.<br>
</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> </div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><br>
